The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe it won't be long before it's ready.
That the Czech mobile service providers work at all costs in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price for a text message here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile communications providers SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a battle dance.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100%.
On the other hand, mobile service providers are happy to complain that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) named Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no place for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find any frequency).
But there is one other option - a virtual provider.
Virtually the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market led to a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile service providers had to respond to.
There were similar votes to those in the Czech Republic before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you do not need to look for examples for a long time.
In February of this we reported on the start of the virtual provider mobilizing in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the fifth largest provider in the country.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind mobilization.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers normally profile themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the cheaper than its competitors.
However, as shown by the example of mobilizing in Poland, it can also be a pretty good move to set itself on a non-clerical target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Echte Kerle vällen Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could take a foothold in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment, on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In Czech Republic, mobile service providers mean
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobilizing.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press representative of the financial group Penta, says in a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková.
Indirectly, they confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to do so.
On the contrary, they try to do everything in their power to ensure that no potential competitor emerges.
Your interest in a virtual mobile service provider has long been showing the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
With some of them we were already able to reach negotiations," said the press spokesperson of Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe now's a better time.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is highly specific to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Martina Kemrová's press spokesperson adds in rare accordance with the O2 statement: "Up to now, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project that could be built on."
And she adds: "The network of T-Mobile will hardly show up a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At that moment, we should already have a specific offer to be able to think so in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider to be the best from the point of view of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area lies in the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider is called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be facilitated to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can draw on a string when it comes to something also proves the long way to and fro about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was reported by the company T-Mobile when U:fon arrived on the market.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is exactly the argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been reinforced by the entry of a fourth mobile service provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would make high demands on the market itself and in particular its services."
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is astounded.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It has exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem, its very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such agreement has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," says Kristian Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
Representatives of the providers would not be surprised at such a wording.
This is more than a concern of an authority representing consumer interests, which is intended to ensure, among other things, that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristian Chalupa adds: "From abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
But probably the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost already touching consistency of the three mobile communications providers, resulting from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question is whether it is really just a coincidence.
Just as the very same price of petrol at the gas stations is certainly only coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"In this matter, the Authority has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive action, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their market behaviour.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulatory authority," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTÚ, after which telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile service providers have a dominant position in such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile service providers behave remarkably similarly.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they encounter very similar obstacles during negotiations with all suppliers.
The shifting of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act failed to extend the ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but probably they have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking.
Without notice, the operation of any pseudovirtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
They are usually companies that operate in the multi-level marketing sector.
Own mobile telephone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke is that the company appears to the operator as a classic business customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar types of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a breach of the contractual terms with which we will then deal, which may lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding society," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
It is, however, quite unlikely that such a thing does not apply to the operators responsible for mobile communications.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an operation.
Because the activities of these companies do not lead to negligible profits, at the same time, they are not affected by the actual official marketing, in contrast to the actual virtual suppliers.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
Moreover, they have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full access to it like the normal customers of the mobile service providers."
However, the ČTÚ alone would have to be at least strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
Before such a procedure, the mobile service providers close their eyes, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It is added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy the declaration of the providers, they knew nothing of it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As pointed out several times in the text, the market entry of virtual operators led to a significant price decline in the various services.
In practice, in all countries where virtual providers have come into existence, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies, which did not attempt to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers, intervened at these very moments.
If it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator arose, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves all over like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot escape the impression that ignorance in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon emerges, the Czech mobile market may soon be reinvigorating.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discrimination) other stakeholders.
And the Czechs will not finally call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
