The Prague transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport companies as a date on which the first passengers will enter a subway, tram or bus, which will carry an electronic coupon in the bag instead of a paper ticket.
These currently account for about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or one-year coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and record it simultaneously on their chip cards, in the Info Centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons have been available since yesterday via the Internet on the websites of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used until the afternoon by over four hundred customers.
Those who use the Internet can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly for their paper licenses in long queues.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, it is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these places, a switch with trained staff is also available to travellers, advises the prospective person when he buys the Internet and also plays the coupon on the map," says the speaker of the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on self-service vending machines on the Opencard, which are mounted in some subway vestibüls.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, remember the driver's rating, the passengers may already have noticed in the subway stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it should be eighty by the end of the year," adds Opatrný.
The coupon controls an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is simple.
Only the chip card has to be inserted, and the previously purchased coupon is recorded by itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surroundings.
Thus, in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants from the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia mainly enter the capital.
"In the trains that belong to Prague's integrated traffic, the train attendants have reading devices that allow them to check the validity of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organization Rapid. This organisation compiles the timetables for Prague's traffic operators.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's checkout.
When entering, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the open card must be displayed at a marked place at the side of the checkout.
The driver thus controls the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the played coupons, nothing is easier than the driver to ask for this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not drive on suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can, in turn, go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
