The motorists, who can fall back because of the alcohol level, will have to install the `Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for alcohol levels, install in his car this system, which forbids him to start the car in a drunken state. If he is alcoholic then the car does not jump.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report by the Public Prosecutor General's Office, according to which it is a pilot project which will last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialise the driver, which is why he is given a course for the re-education of traffic.
In addition to the State Attorney General's Office, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will be involved.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers, who were shown more than once as a result of driving under the influence of alcohol, were re-introduced.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the breathed air and prevents auto start when the driver has made the alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is found which is higher than permitted.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by those who impose the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the US in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of the infringements in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved annually.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to initiate this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is still available on the Spanish markets, in no business, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and vehicles of public transport.
Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
