Discussion - From the blood that has been safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of her founding, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, which had been shaken by the scandal of the contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, during the 1980s, national blood reserves administered by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and the public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Canadian Government launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light into the circumstances which had led to such a tragedy and working out guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to report, several provinces then set up a committee to develop a new system for the administration of blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started working, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood-staining system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and by working in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before she proudly emphasizes that by the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps aware that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
`And we didn't have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we called for one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, which says that exclusion is applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresss only slowly, as it is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proved that this disease is transmitted over the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution we used has quite a meaning.
In 1999 a much more precise technique for detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the virus to detect itself directly in the donor’s blood, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests previously used.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to reduce significantly the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV infected blood.
`In other words, it means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood preserves before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transmitted via a blood preserve.
I think that today you can feel comfortable when you get a blood transfusion or write it to restore your health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to get the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year has the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We need to monitor continuously', Dr. Décary continues before stressing that Hema-Quebec must also provide a sufficient supply in addition to a secure supply.
`The need is rising because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood-supplier network, which accounts for only 3% of Quebec's blood-supplier population on average.
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who supply their blood are not expected to be ill with AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from the donation for one year.
`With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Missing supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to hold it and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic nowadays that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in blood donation', Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood canned but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which are used almost exclusively in serious burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public cord bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical waste, there is abundant blood from stem cells that can help treat severe diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the introduction of our thousands of cord blood samples, and we plan to reduce more than a thousand annually.
`We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year', Dr. Décary further explains that this program describes the navel cord loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
