The psychology of oversupply - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and therefore overvalue the fault bid.
Neurologists and business researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves to a competition, such as an eBay auction, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto while the others took part in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured in the event of the auction losing, in which the opponent’s excess played an important role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase was explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, economists in the research group have also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete with a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their contributions.
Another group was also promised 15 dollars reward, in case they come out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was merely that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "losing" playing group were prepared for higher stakes than those in the control or "winning" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, these have so far only caused the behaviour observed at auctions with the joy of winning, or of avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we have now prepared a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to seek medical advice
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated at a hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various virus-induced infectious liver disease.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogens, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, cleavage or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to immunise the viruses A and B at least, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Then the yellow fever appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine darkens, and recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth is infected in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and cancers of the liver.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a dubious way - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who have undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
At present, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the hospital doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is known to be curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus banishing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the world day of hepatitis, which is the first time patient representations have been held worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
