During the test, a sparking device was attached to the left hand, which the electric shocks gave off.
The participants were asked to focus strongly on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other, Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as reassuring.
The test subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during this time, while they should either look at the religious, or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "in security" at the sight of the mother of God as if they were "careful" and felt "rest and peace".
