Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historic cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This image of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the large urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-saddle complexes in the periphery, in the long term means death for the single-saddle cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inviolable and irrevocable, but also carries the trains of a cultural crime.
Affected are mostly historical places full of memories, "it is like losing a friend with whom one has laid off a piece of road full of emotions," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a probably forever lost cinema world.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak clearly: over the past five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these certificates paid most of the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This testifies to the fact that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas have been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years Lombardy is leading the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and Emilia Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "although it is useful that new structures also arise, but first of all the preservation of the already existing, because closing a hall in the city, are not all his regular customers willing to visit instead of the old one multiplexkino in the periphery.
And here remains the missing bill for the fund of the trade union outside of eight: the debt burden recorded by the State is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to obtain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be necessary".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which has decided, because of fears about the old cinema halls, to protect it by means of an agreement between the community and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy, which aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax advantages for cinema operators and benefits for the public regarding local transport: it will be allowed to drive into the traffic restricted areas of the centre and also to park at less favourable parking fees.
"It is an enjoyable initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But certainly we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to set up something against the superpower of multiplex rooms, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of the traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closing of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "NUovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had played with the thought for ten years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid seeing the dusty posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the community to the interests of the Mafia group Piromalli.
The charges of the attorneys of the Antimafia authorities of Calabria against the mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning in Mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the Clan and the public administration, as well as his nephew, was also taken in handcuffs: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been sentenced to a compensation sum of 10 million euros because of the involvement in criminal associations of the Mafia.
"Any kind of moral and legal standard disregarded," the lawyers wrote, "the two local authorities had decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for consulting activities."
"The Mafia Group was thus made possible – as the judges said – by official means to enter the Councilhouses and to participate in public administration's policy."
The President of the Regional Committee of Calabria Agazio Loiero does not deny that in his region it is "all but an exception to encounter connections between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such connections are practically unavoidable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who get a white vest."
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July with which, according to the police of the Clan Piromalli was decapitated.
Since the end of the last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and at that time due to alleged connections between organised crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the Central Right Coalition after the election of May 2006.
He shouted scandal as the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the council.
He was interested in the Deputy Minister Marco Minniti, who accused him of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges, in connection with the arrest warrant of this morning, explained that the Piromalli clan had even dared to request an amendment to the A3 project.
A hearing action in connection with the Dal Torrione case investigations has shown the willingness to respond to the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – thus making the public administration's actions identical with the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the greats run up.
It is a non-sealing source of money that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and only now seems to understand the great energy companies of the world.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources on which now all look, and also seek to occupy, such as giants as Chevron.
The possibility of gaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years, and these studies have not increased significantly since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke in about 1980, the idea of marine energy was forgotten, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pressing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the worldwide energy demand could be met by ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy produced by nuclear power stations at the moment.
In addition, the currents and tides would be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are relying on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – according to the speaker of a company known to the U.S. giant in the Wall Street Journal – and weighs the possibility of working with us."
This is about obtaining approval from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the Alaska coast.
This is not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil will continue to be promoted by the US in Alaska, and President Bush recently initiated the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; the details are not known, but observers speak of an increasing interest.
Still worthy of improvement.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still emerging, not least because the last doubts have not been clarified by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which move the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmers over pistons and cylinders.
This one drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The power is then sent via underwater pipelines to the coast.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot with the help of underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movement during the tides triggers the turbines, which feed through the resulting rotational movement of the generator.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power Generation Research, a special interest is immediately deserving of the potential in the ages.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely the tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest already 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are planned for 2009.
